##100,000 people petitioned and 229 scientists joined together to criticise whether Britain's "herd immunity" is a gamble?

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to clear the fog, to seek the truth, to watch the Times.

"Let the virus spread slowly in the UK, without stopping it,

Most people get sick and then recover to achieve the ultimate goal of herd immunity."

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
British Prime Minister Boris Johnson: "The new crown pneumonia epidemic is the worst public health crisis of our generation. " Photograph: CBS

British Prime Minister Boris Johnson announced after a Cobra Emergency Planning Committee meeting on March 12 that Britain had entered the second phase of the epidemic, "Delay. ". Bloomberg interpreted it as allowing the virus to spread slowly across the UK, without stopping it and allowing most people to recover from the disease for the ultimate goal of herd immunity.

A new policy after the "deferral" phase is to "stop testing people with mild illness" . The government has advised all people with cough, fever and other symptoms to be quarantined at home for seven days, and those with less severe symptoms should not call the UK's 111 medical helpline unless their symptoms worsen.

In addition, Johnson announced a series of measures including banning schools from allowing students to travel abroad, advising people over the age of 70 not to travel in the near future, and re emphasizing the importance of hand washing, but did not cancel mass gatherings, and they didn't close the schools. The government considers the cancellation of mass rallies to be one of the "least effective" measures, which would only "reduce" the UK's highest number of cases by 5 per cent.

The new coronavirus is likely to turn into a "seasonal flu-like presence" that occurs every year if the vast majority of people can build up a herd immunity to the virus, according to Patrick Valeins, the government's chief science officer, then more people will benefit. "that way we can reduce transmission and protect vulnerable groups. "

UK Government Chief Science Officer Valeins explains his strategy for mass immunization (Source: Sky TV screenshot)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In the field of epidemiology, herd immunity means that a significant proportion of members of a population with immunity can, with a high probability, block the secondary transmission of an infected person, thus protecting the rest of the non-immune population from infection.

The British government's team of experts believe that if very drastic measures are taken, when these measures are lifted, the epidemic will bounce back, meaning the virus could be circulating again next winter, by then Britain's epidemic prevention system had been overloaded for a year, with unpredictable consequences.

"If you try very hard to suppress something, it will bounce back when you release it, and it will bounce back at the wrong time, " says Valeins, "It is hoped that these measures will increase the UK population's immunity to the new coronaviruses, thereby relieving pressure on the health system. "

On March 13th the Department of Health updated its guidelines for testing for the virus to include three categories of UK residents: those in intensive care are given the highest priority, followed by those whose doctors judge they are in need of hospital treatment; Patients with cluster infection from schools, nursing homes and other places will be tested after severe or moderate illness. Patients with mild symptoms will not be able to get the virus tested in time.

Valeins insists that no single measure will satisfy everyone. It is only from a scientific point of view that the most reasonable and appropriate course of action that the British government can take at this stage is to delay the peak of the epidemic as long as possible, while at the same time someone has to be infected and produce antibodies, achieve this goal between this summer and the next winter.

The latest figures released by the UK Health Authority on March 14 showed that the total number of confirmed cases of new pneumonia in the UK has reached 1,140, an increase of 342 from the previous day's figure and the cumulative number of deaths has doubled from the previous day to 21.

"The theory is the theory, the actual situation still remains to be observed, different countries have different systems, national conditions, coping strategies are different. There is still time for the UK to change measures if it is found not feasible,"Hu Shanlian, a professor of health economics at the public health at the Fudan University, told China Newsweek.

However, the population immunity threshold of different infectious diseases viruses is different. Diseases such as smallpox and measles require as much as 80 to 90 percent of the population to be immunized. The British government's panel now believes that if 60 per cent of the population is immunised by self-cure or vaccination against mild cases of the new coronavirus, the "herd immunity" criterion can be met.

The strategy has been derided by netizens as "testing poison with one's body" , "being willing to die" , and even compared to "queuing for measles" , this is a popular practice in Europe and the United States: Parents Invite measles infected people to play with their children, so that children infected with measles, thereby producing antibodies.

The calculation of the population immunity threshold depends on the number of viral Basic reproduction number R0, the average number of people infected by a patient. "The higher the R0 value, the higher the proportion of infection needed to form a population immunity, " explained Ning Yi, a professor at the Public Health, Peking University, the number of individuals infected is less than 1, or R01, when the epidemic is under control.

"The practice of 'postponing' is actually to move the peak of infection backward, prolong the epidemic period and reduce the peak value, similar to the normal distribution. According to British calculations, a short-term epidemic results in a death rate with a peak infection rate that is relatively consistent with a long-term, low-peak death rate, " Ning said, reducing the peak value can avoid the medical run-out in theory, and make more rational use of medical resources.

But there is also a problem, new coronavirus pneumonia is a new disease, many data is not yet known, exactly how much virus infection to produce immunity without disease, and now can not find this threshold. For example, Ning Yi said that the ideal state is the threshold range is relatively large, easy to control, but if the threshold range is small, if for 100 ~ 101, will be infected with a serious illness. According to the status of severe patients with new coronary pneumonia, treatment time is long, and then will occupy medical resources.

"The UK has prepared a script, but what if the virus doesn't act according to the script? That's what everyone is worried about, " Ning said.

At 67 million people in the UK, 60% of the infected, or 40 million people, are infected, and at a conservative rate of 1% , or 400,000 people above the "threshold" of immunity, according to the latest 3.4% global case fatality rate published by WHO officials, that is, 13,600 people could die in the experiment.

"The UK's strategy of delaying a rise in herd immunity to stop the new coronavirus epidemic is a very passive option, and the result may be that in today's Italy, the strategy is inhumane in terms of the high mortality of the new coronavirus, " said Zhang Zuofeng, associate dean of Ucla's public health and a senior tenured professor of epidemiology.

Ning Yi analysis, "containment-delay-research-solution" thinking is right, the key is that the measures are not implemented, the containment phase of the restrictions are not strong enough, for purposes such as protecting privacy, it is also impossible to track, public information infected, therefore, we can't delay it, the third stage is a miracle drug, it's not very practical, even if we have a vaccine or a miracle drug, it's still a phase III trial, and it's not likely to be clinically effective until the summer.

According to the new coronavirus infection number-time curve, after a long, smooth accumulation of early, there will be a point at which the outbreak, double up. "there is still time for management in the UK, and if we look at it for another week, the data could change significantly, " Ning said, adding that the UK would follow the practice of the US, which declared a state of emergency on the 13th, restricting flights and closing schools, "The UK may soon make a move as well, " Ning said.

"I have to be honest with the British public: Many families will lose their loved ones early, " Johnson warned at a news conference, "The new crown pneumonia epidemic is the most serious public health crisis of our generation, " he said.

"The British approach, which looks like a high-stakes gamble, actually has some scientific basis, " Huang Yanzhong, a professor at the School of Foreign Affairs and International Relations at West-east University and a senior fellow for Global Health at the Council on Foreign Relations, told China Newsweek, this is a combination of the virus and its epidemic characteristics, national mobilization capacity, national health carrying capacity, population structure, and so on, the final decision-making, has missed the early stage of containment, and because personal information can not be traced for reasons such as privacy, "it can be said that the options for Britain were limited, " Huang said, "In effect, the Prime Minister has spoken out what others have not dared to say, as has been done before. "

On March 14th a group of 229 scientists from British universities published an open letter arguing that the government's current strategy of prevention and control would put additional pressure on the NHS, co-signers of the letter also criticised the government's chief science officer, Patrick Valeins, for "spreading the infection to immunise the population" .

By the morning of the 14th local time, more than 100,000 people had signed the petition, calling on the British government to take a more active approach to stop the spread of the outbreak. The petition says it is necessary for Britain to follow Italy's example by restricting all non-essential inter-communal movement, as well as large gatherings. Under British rules, once the number of petitioners exceeds 100,000, parliament should consider debating the issue.

Professor Jimmy Whitworth, of the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, said: "I am surprised that stronger measures have not been put in place, but I expect them in the next week or two. "
